# Task Manager (__PROJECT_LABEL__)

Use this skill for task capture and task lifecycle updates in this project ("__PROJECT_ID__").

This folder was generated by the **claude-task-manager** installer (`install.sh`) — the real
table (tasks.json/context.json/events.jsonl) lives under the claude-task-manager project, in
`data/__PROJECT_ID__/`, NOT in this project. The `task.sh` here is a **wrapper**
that targets that data directory — the calling pattern otherwise stays exactly the
same as before.

## Trigger

```json
{
  "activation": {
    "anyPhrases": [
      "add a task",
      "create a task",
      "track this task",
      "task status",
      "mark this done",
      "block this task",
      "what tasks do we have"
    ]
  },
  "movement": {
    "target": "desk",
    "skipIfAlreadyThere": true
  }
}
```

Also use this skill even when those exact phrases are absent if the latest user message is an actionable work request. If the user asks the agent to do something, that request must become a task before the agent proceeds.

## Storage location

The authoritative store lives under the **claude-task-manager** project (not in this repo):

- `data/__PROJECT_ID__/tasks.json` — the Kanban board (source of truth for tasks).
- `data/__PROJECT_ID__/context.json` — the **user context** (source of truth for the user's intent, decisions, and init prompt; see "User context" below).

NEVER read/write these files directly from this project — always go through the `task.sh`
wrapper below (it resolves the correct data directory).

## Token-efficient CLI (`task.sh`) — THE ONLY WRITER

For handling `tasks.json`, **do not** re-read/rewrite the whole file (it costs a lot of
tokens). Use the `task.sh` wrapper bundled with the skill (jq-based), which produces
compact output and writes atomically (it automatically maintains the timestamp and
history/notes entries). The script is on the Claude settings allowlist and can run
without a permission prompt.

> **HARD RULE — NEVER edit the JSON directly; only use `task.sh`.** Do not modify either
> `tasks.json` or `context.json` with the `Write`/`Edit` tools, and do not write back "the
> full JSON" by hand. Every mutation (both task AND context) must go **exclusively**
> through `task.sh` commands — this way there is a single atomic writer, with consistent
> timestamps and history, and no corrupted/duplicated state. This applies to the **main
> agent and EVERY subagent/teammate**. For reads, use `task.sh`'s query commands
> (`summary`, `list`, `get`, `ctx` …); only use `Read` on the JSON as a last resort, and
> never to write. (For `context.json`, use the `ctx-*` commands — see below.)

> **If `task.sh` fails with `Permission denied` / `Could not open file … tasks.json`:** the
> board's data files are owned by `root` (a container that ran as root wrote them — happens on
> native Linux Docker). The file is `-rw-------` root:root, so the host user can neither read
> nor write it, and `task.sh` itself dies at the `jq` read — this is NOT fixable by writing
> the JSON directly (that fails too). Ask the user to run **`ctm fix-perms`** (reclaims
> ownership; no `sudo` needed while the board is up), then retry. A restarted board (`ctm up`)
> keeps running as the host user, so it won't reoccur.

Canonical calling form (with the FULL absolute path, from any working directory):

```
__TASK_SH_PATH__ <command> [args] --as <agent>
```

> **REQUIRED: `--as <agent>` on every non-meta command.** Add your own name to every
> `task.sh` call: the **main agent uses `--as main`**, a teammate uses its own label
> (`--as backend-auth`). This is recorded as the `by` field on every event. Without
> `--as`, non-meta commands **throw an error**. Exceptions (no `--as` needed): `help`,
> `inbox`, `init`, `validate`, `restore`, `raw`.

> **No permission prompt needed — call it DIRECTLY, as a bare command.** ALWAYS call
> `task.sh` with the absolute path above, as a **standalone** command — no `cd`,
> `&&`/`||`, redirects (`2>&1`), or `$VARIABLE`. Claude Code requires a permission
> prompt for chained commands **segment by segment**, so a `cd … && …task.sh …` form
> would trigger a prompt. The script already has `TM_DIR` baked into itself (see
> `claude-task-manager/engine/projects.sh`), so `cd` is unnecessary anyway. The script
> is on the project allowlist (`.claude/settings.local.json`, `Bash(…task.sh:*)`), so
> the bare absolute call runs without a permission prompt.

Most common commands (always call with the FULL absolute path — copy it as shown):

- `__TASK_SH_PATH__ summary --as main` — counts by status (a quick "where do we stand" overview).
- `__TASK_SH_PATH__ list [status] --as main` — compact list in `id [status] title` form.
- `__TASK_SH_PATH__ get <id> --as main` — the full JSON of a SINGLE task (not the whole file).
- `__TASK_SH_PATH__ add <id> <title> [desc] --as main` — a new task with `todo` status, with all required fields.
- `__TASK_SH_PATH__ status <id> <status> [note] --as main` — status change + history entry.
- `__TASK_SH_PATH__ note <id> <text> --as main` — append a note. Start it with an ALL-CAPS
  keyword + `:` and the board shows a colored phase badge on the note (and on the card): e.g.
  `RESEARCH`/`KUTATÁS`, `PLAN`/`TERV`, `DECISION`/`DÖNTÉS`, `IMPL`/`FIX`/`REFACTOR`,
  `DONE`/`KÉSZ`, `BLOCK`/`BLOKK`, `WARNING`/`FIGYELEM`, `VERIFIED`/`TEST`, `USER`, `HANDOFF`.
  Free text works too (neutral badge) — the keyword is what makes a long note scannable.
- `__TASK_SH_PATH__ set <id> <field> <json-value> --as main` — set an arbitrary field (quote strings like `'"main"'`).
- `__TASK_SH_PATH__ find <text> --as main` — and likewise: `… history <id>`, `… ids`, `… archive|unarchive|rm <id>`.

**Structured fields and workflow commands** (instead of encoding them into title/notes text):

- `… priority <id> <low|normal|high|urgent>` — priority (drives `next` ordering; note `list` is NOT priority-sorted).
- `… tag <id> <add|rm> <tag>` — tags (e.g. `frontend`/`backend`/`test`).
- `… module <id> <area>` — functional-area label (`assignedModule`), e.g. `event-edit`/`billing`; free text, empty string clears it. A separate axis from the work-type `tag`; filter with `list --module <area>`.
- `… assign <id> <agent>` — sets `assignedAgentId` (more convenient than `set` for claiming). Use the **stripped identity** from the roster below, NOT the `ctm-`/`tm-` launch name.
- `… claim <id>` — **atomic, race-safe** take: flips a `todo` to `in_progress` AND assigns it to the `--as` caller in one locked write; refuses if another agent already claimed it (prevents two agents double-working the same task). Teammates use this to pick up work.
- `… handoff <id> <to> [note]` — reassign to `<to>` AND send them a **directed** inbox ping (`‼️`). The explicit way to route a finding/bug/sub-task to another teammate.
- `… review <id> [reviewer=main] [note]` — move to `review` AND route it to a reviewer (assigns them + pings their inbox), so review has an owner instead of silting up. Teammates close their part with this instead of a bare `status … review`.
- `… review-queue [reviewer]` — tasks in `review` (oldest first) with age; optionally just one reviewer's queue. Main's "what's waiting for my sign-off" view.
- `… stale [--older-than 24h] [status...]` — held-but-idle tasks (default `in_progress`+`review`) past a threshold, by `lastActivityAt`. Surfaces stuck/forgotten work to re-route.
- `… files <id> [add|rm <abs-path>...]` — the source files a task touches (absolute paths, unique; no sub-op lists them). A standard duty on every task — the machine-readable pointer to the change, kept out of the free-text note.
- `… checklist <id> [add <text>...|done <item-id>...|undo <item-id>...|rm <item-id>...]` — the small steps INSIDE a task (no sub-op lists them). **You (main) write the items; teammates only tick them off** — see the workflow below. Items get a stable `c<n>` id, never reused. Use it for steps that don't deserve their own task — a real sub-task belongs in `dep`/`handoff` instead. Marking a task `done` with unchecked items warns but doesn't block; ticking the last item does NOT change the status by itself.
- `… dep <id> <add|rm> <other-id>` — dependency (`dependsOn`): `id` waits on `other-id`; includes cycle and existence checks.
- `… deps <id>` — what this task is waiting on and what it blocks.
- `… next [--claim]` — the next recommended `todo` task (no open dependency), sorted by priority. `--claim` atomically takes it (see `claim`).
- `… list [status] --tag <t> --agent <a> --priority <p> --module <m> --all --json` — filtered/machine-readable list.
- `… status-many <status> <id...>` — move multiple tasks to one status in a SINGLE atomic write.
- `… reopen <id> [status]` — reopen a closed/archived task.
- `… validate` — schema check (required fields, status, priority, broken dependencies, duplicate ids).
- `… restore` — restore the most recent pre-write backup (`tasks.json.bak`).
- `… inbox <agent>` — events generated by OTHER agents since `<agent>`'s cursor (meta command, no `--as`).

Full help: `__TASK_SH_PATH__ help`. Only read the full JSON (`… raw` / Read) if the task
cannot be accomplished with the commands above.

## User context (session continuity)

Beyond individual tasks, maintain a durable **user context** so that work can be resumed in a
**fresh session** without re-interviewing the user. Store it (via `task.sh`'s `ctx-*`
commands) — never with `Write`/`Edit`:

- Session starts and the file is missing → `ctx-init "<initPrompt>" "<goal>" --as main`.
- The user makes a **decision** → `ctx-decision "<topic>" "<decision>" "<rationale>" --as main`.
- A permanent rule/constraint is stated → `ctx-constraint "<text>" --as main`.
- An open question arises / is resolved → `ctx-question add|rm "<text>" --as main`.
- The active focus changes → `ctx-set currentFocus '"<task-id or text>"' --as main`.

At the start of every session, **read `__TASK_SH_PATH__ ctx` first**, and let it guide the work.

## Roles — the main agent coordinates, teammates execute

The **main agent does NOT do the implementation work itself.** Its job is to capture and
break down requests into tasks, `add`/`assign` them, coordinate, review, and decide the
handoff — it does **not** write the code/dev work directly. All actual implementation and
follow-up work is **delegated to teammate subagents** — the project's `ctm-*` agents (and
`tm-*` agents where present). The main agent only: plans, adds/assigns tasks, reviews the
result, and decides the `review → done | assign+todo` handoff.

- When a request is actionable, `main` creates the task(s) and **assigns** them to the
  appropriate `ctm-*` / `tm-*` teammate (`… assign <id> <agent> --as main`) instead of
  starting to implement.
- Each teammate claims its task, moves it to `in_progress`, does the work, and updates
  status with its own `--as <name>` (never `--as main`).
- `main` stays the coordinator across the whole loop: fill teammate queues, keep tasks
  assigned, and on `review` decide `done` or reassign.
- **Model choice on launch (token efficiency).** The `ctm-*` frontmatter `model:` is only a
  **default** — the main overrides it **per launch** via the Agent `model` parameter, so
  every teammate can be started with **either `haiku` or `sonnet`**, chosen by task weight:
  - `haiku` — mechanical / small, well-scoped edits (rename, move, boilerplate, a single
    localized change with a clear spec).
  - `sonnet` — investigation, planning, multi-file or ambiguous changes, and any testing.
  When unsure, prefer `sonnet`. **Never use `opus`, `fable`/`claude-fable-5`** — teammates
  run only on `haiku` or `sonnet`.

### Teammate roster — the base set

For the base agents the **launch name (`subagent_type`) and the task-manager identity
(`assign` / `--as`) are the SAME string** — there is nothing to strip or translate:

| Agent | Use it for |
|---|---|
| `backend-dev`       | backend work |
| `frontend-dev`      | frontend work |
| `investigator`      | read-only code investigation; usually first in the chain |
| `playwright-tester` | verifying behavior in a real browser; usually last in the chain |

**`playwright-tester` is environment-dependent:** it can only do its job where the Playwright
MCP server is available. If it isn't, don't launch it — do the verification yourself, or hand
it to the human, and say which it was. Never let a task pass as "verified" because the agent
that would have checked it couldn't run.

The project may also ship `tm-*` variants — their identity is the name WITHOUT the `tm-`
prefix (e.g. `tm-frontend` → `frontend`), so check the `--as` line inside each `tm-*` agent
before assigning. **Watch for identity collisions:** two agents that claim tasks under the same
`--as` name will fight over the same queue. `ctm agent add` refuses the base names for exactly
this reason, but a hand-written agent definition can still collide — if a task keeps getting
picked up by the wrong teammate, that's the first thing to check.

### How many teammates to run

**Run 3-4 teammates at a time — no more — and keep feeding them.** The right default is the
base set: `investigator`, `backend-dev`, `frontend-dev`, plus `playwright-tester` where the
environment allows it. This is a limit on CONCURRENCY, not on total work: a teammate that
finishes its task stays alive and takes the next one.

- **Don't stop a teammate to start another.** Spawning is expensive and throws away everything
  it has learned about the codebase. Send it the next task instead.
- **Feed them, don't batch them.** When a teammate reports back, give it the next task right
  away rather than waiting for the others to finish. A blocked teammate is idle capacity.
- **More than 4 in parallel ONLY if the user asks for it.** Beyond that the coordination cost
  (routing, review, merge conflicts on the same files) grows faster than the throughput, and
  two teammates editing the same file will undo each other's work.
- **Fewer is fine.** If the work is one-dimensional, one teammate is the right number — don't
  spawn a frontend-dev for a task with no frontend in it.

## Required workflow

Every step goes through `task.sh` (never a direct JSON write). **Add `--as main` to
every non-meta command** (as the main agent); a teammate uses its own `--as <name>`:

1. Before handling an actionable request, `__TASK_SH_PATH__ summary --as main` / `list … --as main`.
2. At session start, `__TASK_SH_PATH__ ctx --as main`; if missing, `ctx-init "<initPrompt>" "<goal>" --as main`.
3. If the last user message is actionable and there's no active task for it, immediately `__TASK_SH_PATH__ add <id> "<title>" "<desc>" --as main`. On add, set **priority** only when it isn't ordinary — `… priority <id> high|urgent --as main` for blockers or user-flagged urgency (`normal` is the default; don't set it explicitly). This is what makes a teammate's `next` pick the right task first. Optionally label the **functional area** with `… module <id> <area> --as main` when filtering the board by area (`list --module <area>`) is useful — a separate axis from the `frontend`/`backend` work-type tags.
4. **When the task breaks into steps, record them as a checklist ON the task — this is main's job, not the teammate's.** You are the one who planned the work; a teammate that has to invent the steps has already lost the plan. Write them at `add` time (or as soon as the breakdown is clear), and the teammate then just ticks them off as it goes, so progress is visible while the work is running rather than only in the closing note. Keep the boundary: a step that needs its own owner or status is a TASK (`add` + `handoff`), not a checklist item.
   `__TASK_SH_PATH__ checklist <id> add "extend the save service" "add the route" "wire up the form" --as main`
5. Before starting work, the task should be `todo`, or run `__TASK_SH_PATH__ status <id> in_progress --as main`.
6. If the work cannot proceed, `__TASK_SH_PATH__ status <id> blocked "<reason>" --as main`.
7. When done, `__TASK_SH_PATH__ status <id> done --as main`. With unchecked checklist items left, this warns on stderr but still goes through — either tick them, remove the ones that turned out unnecessary, or accept the warning knowingly.
8. If user review/confirmation is needed, `__TASK_SH_PATH__ status <id> review --as main`.
9. `task.sh` writes every mutation atomically and maintains the timestamp/history — manually
   writing back the full JSON is unnecessary and forbidden.

## Status rules

- New actionable requests start as `todo` unless work has already begun.
- Move to `in_progress` when the agent is actively working.
- Move to `blocked` when progress depends on missing input, credentials, approvals, or failures.
- Move to `review` when the work is ready for inspection or handoff.
- Move to `done` only when the requested work is complete.

## Board (shared, dockerized interface)

The board is served by the **claude-task-manager** project (docker compose, port 3333),
a **shared** interface for all installed projects — select this project
(**__PROJECT_LABEL__**) from the "Source" picker in the header:

```
cd /Users/mgeri1993/code/projects/claude-task-manager && docker compose up -d
# then: http://localhost:3333/
```

Writes from the board **still go through `task.sh`** (the single-writer invariant is
preserved: atomic lock, history, `events.jsonl`, inbox) — the browser NEVER writes the
JSON directly. `task.sh` calls (agent work) **don't need docker** — the
`__TASK_SH_PATH__` above is a plain host bash script that runs standalone.

